WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:29.540
Music

00:30.000 --> 00:37.000
Okay, so this week we are getting the horses to be attentive to our immediate aids.

00:37.000 --> 00:40.000
So we're putting them through some drills.

00:40.000 --> 00:49.000
So as part of our groundwork, we are just going to get the horses to be very prompt about coming forward with our step and stopping with our step.

00:49.000 --> 00:52.000
So you see here the result of this young horse.

00:52.000 --> 00:56.000
We have a four year old warm blood here and he's mostly distracted.

00:56.000 --> 01:04.000
And so this is a great exercise for him to do to become attentive to the handler and eventually the rider.

01:04.000 --> 01:17.000
So essentially the exercise is you're just going to walk some very consistent steps and then you're going to obviously halt and correct the horse.

01:17.000 --> 01:28.000
They want you want to make sure the horse is standing directly beside you in line with you and their ears are on you and they stop when you stop your legs.

01:28.000 --> 01:39.000
So at first you are going to go through with your voice commands by saying whoa and clucking or saying walk on depending on what your horse is used to.

01:39.000 --> 01:49.000
And then after a while you want to be able to get to a point where the horse is so attentive that they're just watching you the whole time.

01:49.000 --> 02:02.000
To make the corrections, you want to just replace the horse to the exact position to the millimeter where you wanted them to stop in the end.

02:02.000 --> 02:10.000
OK, so that's very important that you're consistent and systematic about the way that you correct them.

02:10.000 --> 02:15.000
And we're going to do this on both sides at the walk and the trot.

02:15.000 --> 02:23.000
So eventually when your horse is really good in the walk, then you can move to the trot and change your hands so that you're on both sides of them.

02:23.000 --> 02:27.000
If we want to ride them on both sides, we must work them on the ground on both sides.

02:27.000 --> 02:41.000
If we want them to be even on both sides, you must work them on both sides.

02:41.000 --> 02:56.000
Good. Make sure that you're praising them a lot every time that they are right and not correcting them and withholding praise when they're not right so that they know the clear difference.

02:56.000 --> 03:03.000
And then when they're standing still, then you can pet them and praise them again with your voice and with your pets.

03:03.000 --> 03:11.000
Another correction we want to make sure is present is you don't want them hanging on the line on the rope.

03:11.000 --> 03:15.000
So they should be on a loose rope, paying attention the whole time.

03:15.000 --> 03:21.000
So whenever you need to use the rope or the whip, in this case, I'm carrying a whip.

03:21.000 --> 03:24.000
You might not always need a whip if your horse is more sensitive.

03:24.000 --> 03:31.000
This horse is not sensitive and could use the correction of the whip.

03:31.000 --> 03:50.000
So whenever you're using the rope, then make sure that you're letting it go so that it can re-neutralize onto a loose rein and the horse is truly following you and looking at what you're actually doing.

03:50.000 --> 03:57.000
So here we have the correction of the trot. So where he started, where he was confused, he was distracted.

03:57.000 --> 04:12.000
So start with a little jog, correct them, go back to the walk for a few steps, make sure that they understand the exercise from the walk again, and then re-invite the trot so that they can understand.

04:12.000 --> 04:22.000
You can see me there really accentuating the halt so that he's extra aware that it's going to happen and he can follow really well.

